8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 218, L.D. 318, “An Act Regarding
10 School Funding and General Purpose Aid for Local Schools”
11 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'Resolve, Directing the Maine Education Policy Research Institute and the
13 Department of Education to Recommend Changes to the Essential Programs and
14 Services Funding Formula'
15 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
16 'Sec. 1. Maine Education Policy Research Institute to review certain
17 essential programs and services components; report. Resolved: That the Maine
18 Education Policy Research Institute shall:
19 1. No later than October 1, 2025, identify updated cost model parameters for the
20 Department of Education to use in simulating projected impacts on school funding.
21 Parameters must include, but are not limited to, the following:
22 A. Transitional recommendations for moderating the special education component's
23 expenditure-based adjustment;
24 B. A minimum index value for the regional adjustment;
25 C. A recommendation for calculating a regional index based on a valid and reliable
26 cost-of-living measure;
27 D. An updated per-pupil amount to more adequately fund instructional staff support;
28 E. A variable student weight for determining economic disadvantage, with higher-
29 poverty units receiving a progressively higher weight;
30 F. Alternative parameters and implementation guidelines for the transportation model;
31 and
32 G. One or more options for incorporating a student economic disadvantage factor into
33 the method for determining the amount of state subsidy provided to each municipality,
Page 1 - 132LR1718(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 218, L.D. 318
314 including, but not limited to, adjusting the local required share of the essential programs
325 and services cost estimate based on the proportion of economically disadvantaged
336 resident students;
4 2. No later than October 1, 2025, identify additional information needed from school
5 administrative units, to be collected by the Department of Education in fall 2025, to
6 examine the per-pupil costs of certain high-cost in-district special education programs and
7 services; and
8 3. Solicit stakeholder input on the results of simulations generated by the Department
9 of Education pursuant to section 2, subsection 2 and submit a report to the Joint Standing
10 Committee on Education and Cultural Affairs summarizing the recommended parameters
11 and results of stakeholder input no later than January 15, 2026.
12 Sec. 2. Department of Education to collect data and conduct simulations
13 of updated parameters for certain essential programs and services
14 components; report. Resolved: That the Department of Education shall:
15 1. Collect data identified by the Maine Education Policy Research Institute pursuant
16 to section 1, subsection 2;
17 2. Simulate the impacts that the parameters proposed by the Maine Education Policy
18 Research Institute pursuant to section 1 would have had on fiscal year 2026 school funding
19 allocations, including the impact of all parameters combined, on the following:
20 A. Total statewide cost of education;
21 B. Statewide mill rate expectation; and
22 C. Local and state shares and state share percentage of the essential programs and
23 services estimated cost of education in each school administrative unit;
24 3. Provide the results of the simulations pursuant to subsection 2 to the Maine
25 Education Policy Research Institute no later than October 15, 2025; and
26 4. Submit a report summarizing the results of the simulations pursuant to subsection
27 2, as well as any other simulations the Commissioner of Education may recommend, to the
28 Joint Standing Committee on Education and Cultural Affairs no later than January 15,
29 2026. The joint standing committee may submit legislation related to the report to the
30 Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.
31 The Maine Education Policy Research Institute shall conduct the work under section 1
32 within existing contracted resources. The Department of Education shall conduct the work
33 under this section within existing resources.'
34 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
35 number to read consecutively.
36 SUMMARY
3377 This amendment replaces the bill, which is a concept draft, with a resolve. The
3388 amendment directs the Maine Education Policy Research Institute to specify certain
3399 elements of the essential programs and services funding formula to be simulated with new
4400 parameters. The Department of Education is required to collect additional data from school
4411 administrative units and conduct simulations of the proposed parameters. The institute is
Page 2 - 132LR1718(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 218, L.D. 318
412 required to solicit feedback from stakeholders on the recommended potential adjustments
423 to the funding formula in light of the forecasts prepared by the department. The amendment
434 directs the department to conduct the reviews within existing resources and the institute to
445 conduct the work within existing contracted resources. The institute and department are
456 required to submit reports with their findings and recommendations to the Joint Standing
467 Committee on Education and Cultural Affairs no later than January 15, 2026.
